[normal]Q3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] That actually leads in to the first question I was going to ask you anyway, which is really how you set your humanitarian budget and how you deal with it
[normal]. 
[normal]You have had a large increase in humanitarian spend and you have explained part of the reason for that of course, in 2012
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]13
[normal]. 
[normal]How far were you able to do that because of the increasing budget, and how far will you 
[normal]be
[normal] able to do it in other circumstances?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: The starting point for the 
[normal]Government
[normal]’s approach on humanitarian and emergency response obviously goes back to the review that Lord Ashdown did in the 2010
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]11 year
[normal]. 
[normal]One of the key things he said 
[normal]was 
[normal]that most people expect humanitarian crisis to be, unfortunately, a growing problem, even as development proceeds in the years ahead
[normal]. 
[normal]The 
[normal]Government
[normal] took a decision then largely on the basis that this is an area of activity where the UK internationally is highly regarded and has a lot of expertise and comparative advantage, so we would organise the Department to make a major contribution on this set of humanitarian
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]related
[normal] issues
[normal]. 
[normal]We have been building the capacity of the Department, and also always plan to be able to respond both to chronic ongoing emergencies and to new sudden
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]onset
[normal] ones, within the way we budget in the Department.
[normal]As you say, the 2013
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]14 year is the one where we have had the substantial increase to deliver the 
[normal]Government
[normal]’s commitment on 0.7%
[normal]. 
[normal]That meant we had substantial additional resources compared with the previous year
[normal]. 
[normal]Equally, we had spent the last several years planning how to use those additional resources
[normal]. 
[normal]The way in which we financed the biggest crisis we have been responding to over the last year, which is the Syria and wider Middle East crisis, was a combination of contingency funding that we always hold for these problems, budgets in the humanitarian departments—the Conflict, Humanitarian and Security Department, CHASE, which you are familiar with—and also some slower
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]than
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]expected
[normal] expenditure on one or two other areas
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, the European Development Fund during the course of the year told us that they expected to need £160
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million less from us than they had previously told us, so that is the combination of ways in which we have funded it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Why did they not put it into the 
[normal]Middle East
[normal] then?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: It could not be EDF from the European side, because the European Development Fund only does African, 
[normal]Caribbean
[normal] and Pacific countries
[normal]. 
[normal]In fairness to them, I do think that the role that ECHO has played, under 
[normal]Kristalina
[normal] 
[normal]Georgieva’s
[normal] leadership, has been really impressive on the 
[normal]Middle East
[normal] crisis and certainly for us they are very important partners.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] The bit that we are never quite clear about is, first of all, what the budget is
[normal]. 
[normal]By definition, you do not know what is going to be presented as a humanitarian crisis, whether it is conflict or natural disasters
[normal]. 
[normal]Presumably when you are setting your budget, you have a provision for that and some contingency fund
[normal]. 
[normal]There comes a point when presumably you 
[normal]say, “We’ve got 
[normal]nothing left.” The concern for us is at what point it prejudices your commitment to 
[normal]spending elsewhere
[normal]. 
[normal]I do not think anybody on this Committee is critical of the fact that the 
[normal]Government
[normal] has put as much as it has, in the circumstances, into 
[normal]Syria
[normal], but there would come a point when for that kind of money you are saying, “This is not a poor part of the world
[normal]. 
[normal]Is that not at the expense of poorer people in poorer countries?” How can you reassure us that the system does not lead to that kind of conflict of priorities?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: At the beginning of the current spending review period, in 2011
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]12, we set out plans for the resources that we would have available, either in the central humanitarian departments to respond on an ongoing basis to humanitarian problems, or in the contingency fund
[normal]. 
[normal]That was always programmed to grow
[normal]. 
[normal]We then have a long history of having to manage unexpected ebbs and flows in the scale of the need, so this is a problem that we have always had and we have to be able to juggle the whole range of the Department’s activities to cope with it
[normal]. 
[normal]The period when this was most acute in the history of the Department was in 2003, when the 
[normal]Government
[normal] decided, following the commencement of the conflict in 
[normal]Iraq
[normal], that we 
[normal]needed to make a really, really 
[normal]big contribution on humanitarian reconstruction
[normal]. 
[normal]We had to find something like £300
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million from a budget then that was, I guess, in the order of £3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]billion or so, so that was a big commitment quickly
[normal]. 
[normal]We had to do that by explicitly taking a set of decisions about what not to do
[normal]. 
[normal]We closed down, as you may recall, a number of programmes in middle
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]income countries at that time, in order to finance that commitment.
[normal]We have not faced that challenge on the same scale
[normal]. 
[normal]Even with the very major response we are making to the Syria crisis, the scale of our activity there, which may be 2
[normal]% or
[normal] 3% of the Department’s total budget this year, is not such as to do significant damage to all the other things the 
[normal]Government
[normal] has committed to on development.
[normal]&#xa0;
