[normal]Q10[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] There has been a large reduction in budget support
[normal]. 
[normal]Is that large reduction down to the fact that 
[normal]Minister
[normal]s in the Department have lost faith in providing aid in this way?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: Thank you, Mr McCann
[normal]. 
[normal]Maybe I could start and ask Joy to come in
[normal]. 
[normal]When budget support was introduced about 15 years ago, in its modern variant anyway—budget support was part of the Department’s 
[normal]and the Department’s 
[normal]predecessor
[normal]s’
[normal] programme going back to the 1940s and 1950s—there were essentially four objectives that 
[normal]Minister
[normal]s had
[normal]. 
[normal]The first was to support macro
[normal]-
[normal]economic stability at a time when lots of countries were coming out of a period of high inflation, with lots of pressure on the external accounts, and some resources to help deal with that big problem was one objective
[normal]. 
[normal]The second was to support recurrent cost financing, essentially paying teachers and health workers for the core essential work that needed to be done to meet the MDGs in countries that were not able to raise enough of their own tax to do that
[normal].
[normal]The third was to provide an incentive and a means of supporting public financial management reform and public expenditure
[normal] reform
[normal]. 
[normal]The fourth was to make as rational as possible the system by which all of the donors support an individual country, against a background where, as a lot of you have seen, too many finance 
[normal]Minister
[normal]s in the poorest countries spend too much of their time having to talk individually to donors about little things, rather than running their country
[normal]. 
[normal]Those were the four objectives 15 years ago
[normal].
[normal]What has happened is there has been a lot of progress in the 17 or 18 countries where we were doing especially general budget support on those objectives
[normal]. 
[normal]The core reason why we do less of it now is 
[normal]that 
[normal]countries have progressed
[normal]. 
[normal]That is a good thing
[normal]. 
[normal]There are some short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term things going on as well and events we had to respond to, and Joy can talk a bit about some of that.
[normal]Joy [bold]Hutcheon[bold]: When I look across the country portfolio, there are two sets of countries
[normal]. 
[normal]There is one where we have a conscious plan to reduce budget support, for the reasons that Mark has talked about
[normal]. 
[normal]That is in countries like 
[normal]Ghana
[normal], 
[normal]Zambia
[normal] and 
[normal]Mozambique
[normal]. 
[normal]As the Committee will be aware, there are three countries at the moment where we have had to effectively suspend budget support, and those are Rwanda, Uganda—which actually is also in the first category a little—and Malawi
[normal]. 
[normal]There are some different pressures going on
[normal]. 
[normal]In those countries, there is a mixture of reasons, but the fiduciary environment and simply the unacceptable level of risk about putting money as budget support into that fiduciary environment is particularly important in 
[normal]Malawi
[normal] and in 
[normal]Uganda
[normal].
[normal]One thing we are seeing, and I think we are going to see more of, is an increase in what we call financial aid, which is money that goes through 
[normal]Government
[normal] systems but is not budget support
[normal]. 
[normal]We are working with a 
[normal]Government
[normal], because the 
[normal]Government
[normal] systems are working and are an effective way of addressing a particular issue, but we are doing it very specifically to achieve a particular set of results or a particular change
[normal]. 
[normal]The fact that budget support is reducing does not mean, per se, that we are stopping supporting 
[normal]Government
[normal]s and using 
[normal]Government
[normal] systems, but we are finding new ways of doing it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] I do not know if it was your answer that led to the Jordanian delegation walking out, but in terms of these four objectives that you mentioned, they can broadly be described as building country capacity
[normal]. 
[normal]In terms of paraphrasing everything you have 
[normal]said
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]do 
[normal]we still believe budget support is a good idea, but the reduction has been down to your success
[normal]?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: That is a very good way of putting it
[normal]. 
[normal]In a way, 
[normal]countries needing less budget support is
[normal] a sign of their progress
[normal]. 
[normal]There will still be cases where part of what we do in a particular country should be budget support
[normal]. Minister
[normal]s have taken a number of decisions along those lines
[normal]. 
[normal]The broader context I would put this in is we are living through the period in human history that has seen the fastest ever reduction of poverty and the fastest ever increase of life expectancy
[normal]. 
[normal]More countries are becoming less reliant on aid and the kind of aid support they need is evolving, so it is basically a good thing if they are building more of their capacity, as you say, and can raise more of their own tax revenue
[normal]. 
[normal]That is an absolutely fundamental thing
[normal]. 
[normal]Countries do not really want to be dependent and we do not want them to be dependent either
[normal]. 
[normal]Those two things going together, as often as not, are success measures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Fiona O’Donnell:[bold] I wonder if I could just follow up, Mr 
[normal]Lowcock
[normal]. 
[normal]You said that a reduction in budget support was a sign of success, because it meant the countries no longer needed budget support
[normal]. 
[normal]Does that mean, in every case when we reduce or end budget support, it is because that country has no longer requested and no longer needs budget support?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: Not in every case
[normal]. 
[normal]There have been the cases Joy mentioned, where maybe we have not had the same degree of confidence in the fiduciary environment or the 
[normal]Government
[normal]’s commitment to improve the fiduciary environment
[normal]. 
[normal]The more cases we have where we are changing the nature of our systems because the country is moving on, the better, from my point of view.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q13[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Fiona O’Donnell:[bold] What assessment have you made of the impact of that reduction in budget support, particularly perhaps on health systems?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: We did a major independent evaluation about four or five years ago now on the impact of budget support
[normal]. 
[normal]It is a really good point
[normal]. 
[normal]I do not think we have done a major exercise like that since then
[normal]—
[normal]maybe we should do that
[normal]. 
[normal]One thing we are very careful to do is to try to be aware of the impact of what we do on what others might do
[normal]. 
[normal]Unfortunately, there is a bit of a herd effect in international development that, particularly in respect of the 
[normal]UK
[normal], people tend to copy a lot of what the 
[normal]UK
[normal] does
[normal]. 
[normal]We are alert to the danger that, if we take a different position in a particular country, others might do that and that could then be detrimental beyond the narrow impact that we make.
[normal]Also, one of the things I mentioned in terms of when countries need budget support less is when they have made progress on increasing their domestic revenue
[normal]. 
[normal]Of course, we want to see domestic resources being put to work on the MDGs
[normal]. 
[normal]Part of the ongoing dialogue is, when we are providing budget support, never mind when we are graduating from it, can you, a country, invest a bit more of your own resources in paying your health workers and teachers, so that they are on that journey
[normal]. 
[normal]Hopefully, there is public demand in the country for that to be an important use of tax resources as well
[normal]. 
[normal]We are alert to the danger of reverses of progress
[normal]. 
[normal]We have not seen that in countries in a significant way, but we are alert to the danger of it.
[normal]Joy [bold]Hutcheon[bold]: To the extent you are asking about when we stop budget support more suddenly because there is a crisis, it is always our first preoccupation to understand how we can continue to support the poor in that country by finding other routes that are acceptable in fiduciary terms.
