[normal]Q50[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] The Secretary of State has made a high priority of improving DFID’s work with suppliers
[normal]. 
[normal]What progress has been made and have you addressed ICAI’s concerns?
[normal]Richard Calvert[bold]: Shall I start off on that
[normal]? 
[normal]As you say, the Secretary of State has challenged the Department very clearly on this and, in many 
[normal]ways,
[normal] the concerns raised by ICAI reflect that
[normal]. 
[normal]We have acknowledged as a Department that we need
[normal]ed
[normal] to strengthen our work in dealing with suppliers
[normal]. 
[normal]There have been two or three key strands to that and I will describe some of the progress that we have made over the last year or so
[normal].
[normal]Firstly, there was a much more active approach to engaging with and managing our key suppliers—our top 11 or so providers of services to DFID
[normal]. 
[normal]We have now established a key supplier relationship with all of those
[normal]. 
[normal]We have a member of the senior civil service in DFID responsible for each of those relationships
[normal]. 
[normal]We have held our first key supplier conference, which has brought together 
[normal]Minister
[normal]s, officials and key suppliers to work through any kind of key issues
[normal]. 
[normal]Within the Department, we now have a much better sense that we should not think about suppliers just in terms of individual contracts, but we should think in terms of the relationship as a whole
[normal]. 
[normal]It has given us a better basis for managing performance issues with suppliers, where they have arisen
[normal]. 
[normal]We should also say, from our side, it has given us a better basis for getting learning and experience from suppliers
[normal]. 
[normal]As the ICAI report pointed out, this is not simply a purchaser/supplier relationship
[normal]—
[normal]there is an element of partnership in a lot of the work that we do with our key suppliers
[normal]. 
[normal]We have made good progress on that
[normal].
[normal]As Mark alluded to earlier, we have been working hard on the skills and capability side within the Department
[normal]. 
[normal]We will be up to 17 commercial advisers quite shortly, and that is really from a base of zero not very long ago, so that gives us a lot more specialist capacity at professional adviser level, but we will also, by the end of March, have had half of our senior civil servants go through the commercial awareness and training programme
[normal]. 
[normal]The other half will be completed towards the end of 2014.
[normal]One of the things that 
[normal]comes
[normal] out most consistently through all of these strands is the importance of thinking about the commercial and delivery aspects of an intervention at an earlier stage in the process
[normal]. 
[normal]There are some specialist skills that are important in this, but a lot of this is about a change of mindset within the Department
[normal]. 
[normal]When we are thinking about the initial design of an intervention, we are thinking about how we are going to deliver it and what 
[normal]are the most appropriate routes
[normal]. 
[normal]We have talked about some of the choices between multilateral partners or suppliers
[normal]. 
[normal]Probably one of the biggest reasons why we have not been as good in the past always as we should have been is we have sometimes left that judgment 
[normal]too far into the process of programme design, where we have taken design decisions that have effectively led us to a narrow route of options on delivery.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q51[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] Another criticism was project management delivery, which you know that ICAI identified as a weakness and thus was producing less value for money
[normal]. 
[normal]What progress has been made there?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: I will perhaps start and ask Richard to come in
[normal]. 
[normal]I talked a bit earlier about the wide range of things we are doing to improve the quality of programme management
[normal]. 
[normal]One of the biggest most important things is just investing in the skills and incentives and culture of the staff
[normal]. 
[normal]We appointed a head of profession for programme management, who started work six months ago
[normal]. 
[normal]We have had 700 staff through basic training programmes since the beginning of last year and, of those, something like 300 have reached the level where they have some accreditation
[normal]. 
[normal]We are also building a more advanced level of accreditation, so people demonstrably have a better set of skills for programme management than they previously had
[normal].
[normal]We then have a much stronger focus in our management information, which is served up every month to the directors, then to the directors general, and then to me and to 
[normal]Minister
[normal]s, so we can track what is happening on the major programmes
[normal]. Minister
[normal]s are having a regular series of meetings, country by country, on this now, so there is much more scrutiny about what is going well and what is going less well
[normal]. 
[normal]We are asking people a bit more explicitly to be up front in saying what their two or three worry projects are
[normal]. 
[normal]We try to create a positive incentive to share a problem, so it can be fixed, rather than to conceal a problem
[normal]. 
[normal]As you know, we have a kind of index that captures the overall aggregate score of the whole of the portfolio we invest in, and the score is reasonably stable
[normal]. 
[normal]Over time, as all these investments come in, we want to see that score moving up
[normal]. 
[normal]That is evidence of getting better value for money and more successful project completion
[normal].
[normal]Richard Calvert[bold]: You have covered a lot of the key points, Mark
[normal]. 
[normal]For the Department as a whole, the strongest message is we need to be much more consistent in our approach to programme management
[normal]. 
[normal]We have a lot of experience in good programme managers in the Department, but the approach we are taking at the moment is designed to ensure that we have greater consistency across all of our activities and projects, but also that we allow programme managers to spend their time in the most value
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]adding
[normal] way
[normal].
[normal]One of the other aspects of the work on programme management has been to look again at how we produce business cases and where effort goes in the programme cycle
[normal]. 
[normal]We and others have recognised that, although the new business case that was introduced in 2010 has brought in a lot more rigour around important aspects of the appraisal process, it has also taken a lot of time and effort in teams to produce, and we have ended up with business cases taking up relatively more of the time of programme teams than we think is necessary
[normal]. 
[normal]Now, that is not to say that the business case is not always going to be a really critical document or a critical part of the programme process, but we are looking to slightly rebalance efforts so relatively more time is freed up to focus on the delivery and implementation, and to make sure the time spent at the business-case stage is time well spent
[normal]. 
[normal]We are at the moment piloting a slight variation of the business-case format and approach, which keeps the rigour that we introduced in 2010 but takes away some of the unnecessary process and detail.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q52[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
