[normal]Richard Calvert[bold]: Just a couple of very brief points: one of the keys to the change in the business case is actually splitting what was previously the business case into two documents
[normal]. 
[normal]We have what is essentially an appraisal and approval document on the one hand and, on the other hand, a programme delivery plan
[normal]. 
[normal]A lot of the detail that goes into the delivery plan, so 
[normal]how a project is going to be managed and delivered to—its lifecycle—is for the programme team to manage and keep as an ongoing document as the programme goes on
[normal]. 
[normal]The previous business case format asked teams to try to compress that into a single document, so that is one of the big changes.
[normal]The second thing is not just about the document, but it is about really clarifying who is responsible for preparing and signing off a business case, and avoiding what we recognise as a bit of a tendency in DFID for lots of people to want to be involved and lots of people to want to have their say in the design
[normal]. 
[normal]We are just being clear about who takes lead responsibility
[normal]. 
[normal]Mark has talked about the senior responsible owner model that we are going to be introducing
[normal]. 
[normal]There is a bit of culture and behaviour, and there is a bit of change in the documentation
