[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]consuming to do it
[normal], but 
[normal]I am very happy to have a look at whether we have conducted more examples of that sort recently we can share with you
[normal]. 
[normal]For the multilateral organisations, we absolutely expect them as organisations to have a good sense of their total operating costs and admin, and to be tracking that and driving it down
[normal]. 
[normal]I gave the example earlier of how the Global Fund has been doing that
[normal].
[normal]Regarding the proportion of the cost of the World Bank, if you like, and whether that changes when you add in the cost of our supervision of our interest in the World Bank, that element of the cost is so small that it will not make any material difference to an organisation of 15,000 people or something
[normal]. 
[normal]I do not think that is going to move the dial.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q65[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] We have a couple of questions to go, so that we can get to the end
[normal]. 
[normal]It is really about recruitment, retention and promotion, and there are issues we have raised before
[normal]. 
[normal]One is the turnover of staff and the other is their qualifications
[normal]. 
[normal]ICAI rated the Burmese operation good because of its continuity
[normal]. 
[normal]I notice it has all changed since, of course
[normal]. 
[normal]We also saw the value of having a Burmese
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]speaking
[normal] Foreign Office official with us
[normal]. 
[normal]It was quite important
[normal]. 
[normal]You are operating in fragile states, and then we are told that people have difficulty working there
[normal]. 
[normal]Given that is what the organisation does, should you not be recruiting people who expect to go there
[normal]? 
[normal]Should you not be encouraging more people to learn languages
[normal]? 
[normal]Should that not be part of the career development and promotional package
[normal]? 
[normal]We have raised all these issues before, but we are still conscious of the fact that they are not as we would like them to be.
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: Quickly, 1,300 of our staff have recorded language skills on the system
[normal]. Fifty-six 
[normal]languages other than English are spoken
[normal]. 
[normal]Half of those people are fully proficient in another language, and we have been spending more money on language training over the last 12 months or so
[normal]. 
[normal]One of the main reasons why we have our highly capable staff 
[normal]appointed
[normal] in-country is because of the language, cultural and contextual skills that they bring.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q66[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] Could I just ask if that language training is done in-country?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: It is a mixture, Sir Tony
[normal]. 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] It is so important to do it in-country.
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: I completely agree with you
[normal]. 
[normal]One thing that people often do is spend some time with a family or in a community
[normal]. 
[normal]You are learning not just the language, but a whole bunch of other things as well
[normal].
[normal]Chair:[bold] They might learn Nepalese and then you will send them to 
[normal]Zimbabwe
[normal].
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: We need to be intelligent about that
[normal]. 
[normal]You have raised before with us the issue, which is also in your question, about how we get continuity for a longer period or benefit from a longer period from people who spend a chunk of time, say, in Afghanistan but, for reasons I do not at all 
[normal]resile
[normal] from, we will not send to Afghanistan for years and years on end
[normal]. 
[normal]Increasingly, we have cases where people have done a posting, come back and worked on Afghanistan and that region for two or three years in London, and maybe have gone back again
[normal]. 
[normal]We have taken to heart the messages you have given to us on this
[normal]. 
[normal]We will keep paying attention to that and I think we are getting a bit better at it.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I think that is the case with the Burmese staff
[normal]. 
[normal]Some of them are still working on the Burmese programme, but they are doing it from here.
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: I do not know on 
[normal]Burma
[normal], to be honest
[normal]. 
[normal]I would need to look into that
[normal]. 
[normal]There may be one or two people, but I am not sure.
[normal]Joy [bold]Hutcheon[bold]: Could I just give two very quick examples on language training
[normal]? 
[normal]We appointed a new head of DFID Mozambique last year and we had two Portuguese speakers to make the choice between, which was a good position to be in
[normal]. 
[normal]We just appointed the new head for DRC for 2015, and we have done it a year early so that we can make absolutely sure that he has his language skills up to speed before he goes into that post.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q67[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Being what, French or local?
[normal]Joy [bold]Hutcheon[bold]: That is the French language.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q68[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] I was just going to ask if it is a requirement of all UK
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based
[normal] staff who go overseas to learn the language once they are there, because that would seem to me to be an obvious requirement, as a matter of courtesy to the host country?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: It is not a formal requirement for everybody to do that.
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] Should it not be?
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: I am reluctant to add to the number of formal requirements that there are for people to be posted to particular roles
[normal]. 
[normal]In order to be an economist for us in Country X, you need to be a member of the 
[normal]Government
[normal] Economic Service, which has extremely stringent entry criteria
[normal]. 
[normal]You need the right development background as well
[normal].
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] I am not saying you should have to speak the language before you go
[normal]. 
[normal]I am saying, once you are there, it should be part of your contract that you are expected to learn the local language as much as possible
[normal]. 
[normal]Joy [bold]Hutcheon[bold]: In most of the countries where we work, the business of 
[normal]Government
[normal] is conducted in English
[normal]. 
[normal]There are some 
[normal]Lusophone
[normal] and Francophone countries where we do expect people to have learned the language
[normal]. 
[normal]In a number of countries, there is not a single local language and, actually, language is a deeply divisive issue
[normal]. 
[normal]It is not immediately obvious, if you go to 
[normal]Zambia
[normal] for example, which one of the multiple languages in 
[normal]Zambia
[normal] you would learn
[normal]. 
[normal]I think all of our heads of office, in my experience, will make an effort to have a conversational level of language just to be able to deal with the local staff in their office, and to be polite and courteous and demonstrate that they are making an effort.
[normal]Mark [bold]Lowcock[bold]: I would prefer that, to be honest
[normal]. 
[normal]If we made a requirement, people will be paying people to do that as part of a job
[normal]. 
[normal]You cannot make it a requirement and then ask them to do it in their free time
[normal]. 
[normal]Let me take it away and think about it again, but I think I would prefer to stick with the implicit expectation rather than formal requirement.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I think we like what you are saying, but we would look for more results and we will monitor those
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
